Here in Denmark we have one of the world's best medical sectors physical as well as psychiatric. Its still very tough, because one to one conversational therapy is something you need to pay for by yourself. But everything physical except dental issues is provided by the state. This makes it very easy for us as citizens to go for checkups and call on help from our primary care doctors. Our Primary care doctors are as all other doctors trained in therapeutic conversations and use of medicine for psychiatric purposes.

In my case, I pay for my own therapist, I find it works better for me than the group therapy programmes provided by the state. My primary care doctor, however was the first to see the signs of anxiety and get me on medication that instantly helped me. She follows up once every three months and changes my medication depending on my needs, she follows me very closely in my medicinal use, making sure I dont get an addiction or lose control. Furthermore she always takes her time, listening to what I go through with my therapist and providing holistic counsel taking into account my daughter, my husband, my studies and the general realities of life - reminding me what is normal, and what is not. During rough times I use both my therapist and my doctor, but during less hard times, my doctor is more than adequate in handling my therapeutic consults.
My husband had a depression, but never went to therapy, because it was a mild depression. He was prescribed antidepressants and consults with his doctor every 2 weeks, a few months later and he had worked through it. He didnt need a specialist, he just needed his primary care doctor.

You should always be using your primary care doctor as the most central help in your life. They are trained in this and they know you. If you are uncomfortable with your doctor, find a new one - it is ESSENTIAL that you have complete confidence in your doctor. They are our guardian angels and should always stand right behind you protecting your body and mind from harm - that is the essence of their job.

In my opinion, and I'm not a doctor, you are both right and very wrong. Yes, primary health care professionals should be able to give treatment for mental health problems however, you are wrong about how your primary care provider knows you better than a specialist and should therefore be able to provide a good treatment. Where I live doctors easily have 2000+ patients and don't even know the name of most patients... Then when going to see those doctors, you get 10 minutes per appointment to tell them what's wrong with you and within those 10 minutes they decide what kind of medications they can put you on... I mean, I'm sorry, but HOW? 10 minutes is not enough to decide on a treatment, 10 minutes is not even enough to scratch the surface of what is actually going on. And because of that, a lot of people get medicated for the wrong thing. Incorrect medication can have extremely negative consequences for the patients.

So, if after those 10 min, my primary care provider would choose to start a diagnostic process before deciding on treatment then I would easily trust them with mental health care but as long as they keep prescribing within 10 minutes and without an actual diagnosis, I won't trust them...

This video has just confused me even more in terms of who has the ability to help.

To explain, my family doctor explicitly told me they could not prescribe me any psychiatric medications — whether it was anxiety meds specifically recommended by my therapist or my sleep meds I was already being prescribed out of network.
She always said it was because she was a family care physician and therefore was not trained in those medications and so could not treat me. This same doctor also generally refused to handle most of my general care that she should’ve been responsible for, simply due to the fact that I do see many different specialists. To her, if I was suffering from something that could be handled by a specialist (even if it was something as simple as a chest infection) then I would have to go make an appointment with them, not her. She even began to refuse to give me flu shots after a while.
Now, as for the statement that these specialists should care for more complex cases? I’ve been flat out denied from getting psychiatric care, even initial visits with psychiatrists/psychologists have been denied because I’m too complex for them, despite my care being managed very carefully and they would’ve had no part in that other than possibly ensuring no medications were interacting. I’ve even been denied because their office was not wheelchair accessible and they were unwilling to find another way to see me (such as moving into the downstairs physician’s office for my session) and frankly it’s things like this that really scare me about our current medical system. If someone desperately looking for help, with a medical history and several recommendations can’t find help, how do we expect help to come to those broken souls out there who end up acting out in the worst of ways? How are we supposed get help when the medical system has such a specific criteria for who can get it?

This video has just confused me even more in terms of who has the ability to help. 

To explain, my family doctor _explicitly_ told me they could *not* prescribe me any psychiatric medications — whether it was anxiety meds specifically recommended by my therapist or my sleep meds I was already being prescribed out of network. 
She _always_ said it was because she was a family care physician and therefore _was not trained in those medications_ and so could not treat me. This same doctor also generally refused to handle most of my general care that she should’ve been responsible for, simply due to the fact that I do see many different specialists. To her, if I was suffering from something that could be handled by a specialist (even if it was something as simple as a chest infection) then I would have to go make an appointment with them, not her. She even began to refuse to give me flu shots after a while.
Now, as for the statement that these specialists should care for more complex cases? I’ve been *flat out denied* from getting psychiatric care, even initial visits with psychiatrists/psychologists have been denied because I’m *too complex* for them, despite my care being managed very carefully and they would’ve had no part in that other than possibly ensuring no medications were interacting. I’ve even been denied because their office was not wheelchair accessible and they were unwilling to find another way to see me (such as moving into the downstairs physician’s office for my session) and frankly it’s things like this that really scare me about our current medical system. If someone desperately looking for help, with a medical history and several recommendations can’t find help, how do we expect help to come to those broken souls out there who end up acting out in the worst of ways? How are we supposed get help when the medical system has such a specific criteria for who can get it?
As of yet I’m still struggling, unmedicated, with my mental health. They’ll give me all the painkillers I need, but won’t help my brain. That’s the world we live in.

I completely agree with everything you're saying. I just have first-hand experience with my primary care doctor not listening to me, so it sucks. I've been chronically ill physically and mentally, for over 20 years, and not once during that time have I been even close to properly treated for either. I get physical therapy, and get "graduated" the second I improve (because I WANT to feel better and put the work in). I go to group therapy, and individual therapy, and because I have experience controlling myself in public, I come off as composed, and completely fine. Even when I explain that the reason I'm behaving like a "normal" person is because I don't like being vulnerable, and the idea of appearing weak around strangers is scary enough for me to be able to act "normal", they still don't believe me. You basically have to try to kill yourself for anyone to believe you're in mental anguish constantly, and need more than one appointment every two weeks with a counselor who has to type into the computer 75% of the visit.

And doing all of it with Medicaid because you can't work due to chronic physical issues - that's fun. I'm on my 5th counselor in a YEAR at the same place. They all leave when they realize the place doesn't actually help anyone. I've even been told (by my 3rd counselor) that there really is no help to be found.

I don't even live in the sticks, I'm in South Jersey, right outside of Philadelphia. I can't imagine what is happening for those in the boonies and without the meager help of Medicaid.

Mental health is one of the largest problems that we're screwing up royally, and it affects all of society. It makes no sense. I know people feel so much cognitive dissonance when trying to get help.

I walked away with propanolol which is a fine medication for some people but didn’t help whatsoever with what I now know is depression. I mention both cases only to point out that if you feel like you’ve approached your pcp and feel like your mental health is suffering, and they don’t take you seriously or provide you with adequate care you should start looking for a new pcp.
